1. Motivation¶

As a UMD student, have you ever struggled with deciding the courses to enroll in? UMD students are required to have a minimum of 120 credits, in addition to other requirements, to graduate with their bachelors degree. There are so many departments students can take classes from and it can be difficult to choose which course to take from which department. In our group, we had one commonality as UMD CS students. Choosing what classes to take was a constant struggle every semester. Even though we all had 4 year plans prepped, it was persistently changing for a multitude of reasons. A couple of those reasons being classes would fill up before we could sign up or our interests would change. When things don't go to plan it can be very stressful, especially when students have to plan in the middle of their semesters. We would like to help alleviate that stress with this tutorial. In this tutorial, we will analyze UMD departments

3. Data Collection/Curation + Parsing¶

3.1. Data Collection¶

First, we needed to get a list of all departments. This information can be found on Testudo's Schedule of Classes. We learned that there are 184 different departments. We used that information to request a list of courses from PlanetTerp's API, and took the list of courses to get a list of all sections. It takes more than 15 minutes make all the requests, so we ran the code once and saved the DataFrame to a CSV file to save time. The following is the code we used to accomplish this:

{python}
# Create empty DataFrame to hold sections.
df = pd.DataFrame()

# Create department list.
department_list = ['AASP', 'AAST', 'AGNR', 'AGST', 'AMSC', 'AMST', 'ANSC', 'ANTH', 'AOSC', 'ARAB', 'ARCH', 'AREC', 'ARHU', 'ARMY', 'ARSC', 'ARTH', 'ARTT', 'ASTR', 'BCHM', 'BIOE', 'BIOL', 'BIOM', 'BIPH', 'BISI', 'BMGT', 'BMSO', 'BSCI', 'BSCV', 'BSGC', 'BSOS', 'BSST', 'BUAC', 'BUDT', 'BUFN', 'BULM', 'BUMK', 'BUSI', 'BUSM', 'BUSO', 'CBMG', 'CCJS', 'CHBE', 'CHEM', 'CHIN', 'CHPH', 'CHSE', 'CLAS', 'CLFS', 'CMLT', 'CMSC', 'COMM', 'CPBE', 'CPET', 'CPGH', 'CPJT', 'CPMS', 'CPPL', 'CPSA', 'CPSD', 'CPSF', 'CPSG', 'CPSN', 'CPSP', 'CPSS', 'DANC', 'DATA', 'ECON', 'EDCP', 'EDHD', 'EDHI', 'EDMS', 'EDSP', 'EDUC', 'ENAE', 'ENBC', 'ENCE', 'ENCH', 'ENCO', 'ENEB', 'ENEE', 'ENES', 'ENFP', 'ENGL', 'ENMA', 'ENME', 'ENPM', 'ENRE', 'ENSE', 'ENSP', 'ENST', 'ENTM', 'ENTS', 'EPIB', 'FGSM', 'FILM', 'FIRE', 'FMSC', 'FREN', 'GEMS', 'GEOG', 'GEOL', 'GERM', 'GREK', 'GVPT', 'HACS', 'HDCC', 'HEBR', 'HESI', 'HESP', 'HHUM', 'HISP', 'HIST', 'HLSA', 'HLSC', 'HLTH', 'HNUH', 'HONR', 'IDEA', 'IMDM', 'IMMR', 'INAG', 'INFM', 'INST', 'ISRL', 'ITAL', 'JAPN', 'JOUR', 'JWST', 'KNES', 'KORA', 'LARC', 'LASC', 'LATN', 'LBSC', 'LGBT', 'LING', 'MATH', 'MEES', 'MIEH', 'MITH', 'MLAW', 'MLSC', 'MOCB', 'MSML', 'MUED', 'MUSC', 'MUSP', 'NACS', 'NAVY', 'NEUR', 'NFSC', 'NIAS', 'PEER', 'PERS', 'PHIL', 'PHPE', 'PHSC', 'PHYS', 'PLCY', 'PLSC', 'PORT', 'PSYC', 'RDEV', 'RELS', 'RUSS', 'SLAA', 'SLLC', 'SMLP', 'SOCY', 'SPAN', 'SPHL', 'STAT', 'SURV', 'TDPS', 'THET', 'TLPL', 'TLTC', 'UMEI', 'UNIV', 'URSP', 'USLT', 'VMSC', 'WGSS', 'WMST']

# Get sections from all departments.
for department in department_list:
    # Create empty section list.
    section_list = []

    # Get all courses from department.
    courses = planetterp.courses(department=department)

    try:
        # Get all sections from courses.
        for course in courses:
                for section in planetterp.grades(course=f'{department}{course["course_number"]}'):
                    section_list.append(section)
    except:
        print('error')

    # Add sections to DataFrame.
    df = df.append(pd.DataFrame(section_list), ignore_index=True)

# Save DataFrame to a CSV file.
df.to_csv('data.csv')

We can see by counting the number of NaN or null values, there are missing values for professor. This might mean that the section was entered into the database incorrectly. We decided to keep these sections because it is still valuable for course analysis.

Additionally, there are no other missing values in the other columns. We do not need to do additional cleaning for missing data, but we do need to remove courses that have appeared for only 1 semester because it could be the professor's first time teaching that class. We agreed that a professor teaching a class once is not enough to say that they will grade and teach the class the same way next time.

In [162]:

4. Data Management/Representation/Exploratory Data Analysis¶

4.1 Data Management¶

First, we need to add more columns to the DataFrame. Calculating the total number of grades, total number of passing grades, and passing percentage would be useful information. We consider passing as having a C- or above.

In [163]:
# Get the total number grades 
df['number_of_grades'] = df[['A+', 'A', 'A-', 'B+', 'B', 'B-', 'C+', 'C', 'C-', 'D+', 'D', 'D-', 'F', 'W', 'Other']].sum(axis=1)

df['passing_grades'] = df[['A+', 'A', 'A-', 'B+', 'B', 'B-', 'C+', 'C', 'C-', 'Other']].sum(axis=1)
# Get the pass percentages
df['passing_percentage'] = ((df['passing_grades'] / df['number_of_grades']) * 100).round(2)

df['semester'] = df['semester'].astype(str)
df['year'] = df['semester'].str[0:4]

df['department'] = df['course'].str[0:4]

#Goal is to make barcharts of total students per year (2012-2020) for each department.
#Group dataframe by department and year
spy_df = df.groupby(['year','department']).sum().reset_index()

#Create a dataframe with the top most popular departments for each year
top10 = pd.DataFrame()
for i,e in spy_df.groupby('year'):
  e = e.nlargest(10, columns='number_of_grades')
  top10 = pd.concat([top10, e])

plt.figure(figsize=(17,15))

#Make barplots according to year and department
for i,e in top10.groupby('year'):

5. Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning¶

5.1 What will the passing percentage be for the CMSC department in 2021?¶

We know so far that the pass rates for the CMSC department has been increasing over the year. What we don't know is how much and what the percentage might be in 2021. We will make some predictions and find the answer to those questions with a linear regression model.

In [ ]:
# Create a scatter plot of passing percentages over the year

In the violin plot above, it looks like the median pass rate is increasing over time. We want to take a deep look at the distribution of each violin using histograms to determine if they're bimodal, unimodal, skewed, or symmetric.

In [ ]:
# Plot histograms for students passing percentages for individual years
stud_pass_pctg = sns.FacetGrid(data=cs_df, col='year', col_wrap=3)
stud_pass_pctg.map(sns.histplot, 'passing_percentage', bins=15, kde=True)

# Set the size of the plots and the labels
stud_pass_pctg.fig.set_size_inches(15,10)
stud_pass_pctg.set_axis_labels('Student Passing Percentages', 'Count')

# Create and save the xticks in years list
years = []
for i in range(2012, 2021):
    years.append(i)

# Rename the titles of each subplots
for ax, title in zip(stud_pass_pctg.axes.flat, years):
    ax.set_title(str(title) + ' School Year')

# Display the plot
plt.show()

In the above histograms, we can see over the years that the distributions are all left-skewed. In other words, most of the students have a high passing rate since 2012. In addition, all the distributions are unimodal with one peak. What was interesting about the above graphs is that outliers are shown during 2017 and 2020. Thus, let's dive deeper to find the reason why.

In [ ]:
display(cs_df[cs_df['passing_percentage'] <= 40])

In 2017, the CMSC131 class taught by Thomas Reinhardt had many failures and dropouts. It may have been the professor's first time teaching the course, or the students were not motivated enough. We can cannot conclude what exactly happened, but there was a low pass rate of 35%.

In 2020, the same class CMSC131 taught be Fawzi Emad had similar issues with their pass rate of 38%. We cannot say what exactly happened, but we can say that CMSC131 might be a difficult class.

As for the 0 percent passing grade, we see that 7 students withdrew from CMSC435 during the summer of 2020. Some assumptions we can make include the course being dropped or 0 students passed the course.

Now, we want to repeat the average pass rate over the years with a line plot but only with the CMSC department. We want to confirm that our assumptions about the pass rate increasing over time is a good observation.

From the line plot above, there is a positive correlation with pass rate over the years. We want to see the relationship between year and passing percentage, so we will use the scikit-learn module and calculate the linear regression model. We will plot the linear regression on top of a scatter plot.

In [ ]:
cs_df['year'] = cs_df['year'].astype(float)

# Set the plot size
plt.figure(figsize=(15,12))

regline = LinearRegression().fit(cs_df[['year']], cs_df['passing_percentage'])
m = regline.coef_
b = regline.intercept_

# Create a scatterplot to view the regression line
lin_reg_sct = sns.scatterplot(data=cs_df, x='year', y='passing_percentage')

# Set the labels and title
lin_reg_sct.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
lin_reg_sct.set_ylabel('Passing Percentage', fontsize=12)
lin_reg_sct.set_title('Predicted Passing Percentage Over Time', fontsize=20)

# Add the regression line
plt.plot(cs_df[['year']], regline.predict(cs_df[['year']]), label=f'y= {b.item():.4f} + {m.item():.4f}x', color='r')

# Set legend.
plt.legend(title='Linear Regression Model',
           bbox_to_anchor=(1.01, 1),
           borderaxespad=0)

plt.show()

From the graph above, there is a positive linear increasing trend. Our linear regression equation is:

  • y = -1197.7737 + 0.6353x

If we plug in 2021 for x, we get 86.220215. We can conclude that the average pass rate for the CMSC department in 2021 will be 86.22%.

While we did get an accurate prediction for pass rate, we need to address what happened in 2020. The coronavirus pandemic impacted the whole world and the school system. UMD implemented a pass/fail system which heavily influenced the pass rate for Spring 2020. A D- or above was considered passing. We want to know how that affected the pass rate by looking at data between 2019 to 2020.

6. Communication of Insights Attained¶

We ended up with many conclusions that may have been lost in the prose above. We want to gather them all in one place and summarize our findings.

  1. The CMSC department wasn't relevant until 2014. In 2020, it is now the 3rd largest department.
  2. The pass rate of the CMSC department is much lower compared to other departments by almost 7%.
  3. The top 10 courses and professors recommendations may be too old to be useful.
  4. The top 10 Upper Level Concentration recommendations include smaller departments.
  5. The average pass rate for CMSC courses have gotten easier over time from 81% to 87%.
  6. The predicted pass rate for 2021 is 86.22%.
  7. COVID-19 had a significant impact on our analysis. The average pass rate is almost 5% higher than other semesters.

We expected 2021 to follow the same trend. Students were allowed to choose pass/fail this Spring 2021 semester, but the cutoff is C- or above. The predicted pass rate of 86.22% with our linear regression model may be slightly higher than the actual pass rate once grades are released for this semester.
